When the player selects &quot;Y&quot; you&#39;re calling recursively the `playGame()` function:
```cpp
      if (again == &#39;Y&#39;){

        count = 1;
        play = 1;

        int a = random();
        playGame (a);
        // Selecting &#39;N&#39; on the called above game will return to this line
      }
      else if (again == &#39;N&#39;){ 
        // This block will never be reached except for the current game

        win = 0;
        play = 0;
        break;

      }
``` 
If the player decides to stop playing after the second game, code execution will continue just after the `playGame (a);` line, which is the end of the `if (again == &#39;Y&#39;){...}` block, so the `else if (again == &#39;N&#39;){...}` block is never executed for any game except for the last one.

You can resolve this problem in various ways, the simplest of all is to not use recursion (replace `playGame (a);` with `answer = a;` in your code), but I would recommend you to use the opportunity to learn something new and fix the recursive code instead.

More on [Recursion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursion_(computer_science)), [C++ Recursion with example](https://beginnersbook.com/2017/08/cpp-recursion/)

